To access environment variables in a Deno file, you can use the `Deno.env.get()` function. This function returns the value of the specified environment variable or `undefined` if the variable is not set.

Here's an example of how to use `Deno.env.get()` to access environment variables in a Deno file:
```typescript
const envVar1 = Deno.env.get("ENV_VAR_1");
const envVar2 = Deno.env.get("ENV_VAR_2");

if (!envVar1) {
  throw new Error("ENV_VAR_1 is not set");
}

console.log(`ENV_VAR_1: ${envVar1}`);
console.log(`ENV_VAR_2: ${envVar2}`);
```
In this example, we're using `Deno.env.get()` to retrieve the values of two environment variables named `ENV_VAR_1` and `ENV_VAR_2`. If `ENV_VAR_1` is not set, the script throws an error. Otherwise, it prints out the values of both environment variables using `console.log()`.

Note that you need to run your Deno file with the `--allow-env` flag to allow access to environment variables. Here's an example command to run your Deno file:
```css
deno run --allow-env your_file.ts
```
Replace `your_file.ts` with the name of your Deno file. This command grants permission to access environment variables when running your script.
